## 12. End-to-End Flow

### Complete User Journey: Registration → Donation

```
STEP 1: Registration
─────────────────────
User fills Register.js form (name, email, password)
→ POST /api/auth/register
→ Server: password bcrypt-hashed, OTP generated (crypto.randomInt)
→ OTP bcrypt-hashed, stored in User document with 10-min expiry
→ HTTP 201 sent immediately (non-blocking)
→ Background: sendMail() → SendGrid API → email with OTP to user

STEP 2: OTP Verification
─────────────────────────
User sees VerifyOtp.js page (email pre-filled from query param)
→ User enters 6-digit OTP
→ POST /api/auth/verify-otp { email, otp }
→ Server: check expiry, check attempts < 5, bcrypt.compare(otp, user.otp)
→ Match: user.isVerified = true, OTP fields cleared, JWT issued (7d)
→ Token stored in localStorage → redirect to /dashboard

STEP 3: Profile Setup
──────────────────────
User goes to Profile.js → fills blood group, location, age, phone
→ PUT /api/user/update (JWT in headers)
→ authMiddleware validates JWT → attaches req.user
→ User document updated in MongoDB (including locationGeo for geo-queries)

STEP 4: Donor Search
─────────────────────
User opens Donate.js → browser requests geolocation
→ GET /api/donors/nearby?lat=...&lng=...&maxDistance=20000
→ MongoDB $geoNear aggregation returns nearest available donors
→ Map (Leaflet) shows donor pins

STEP 5: Blood Request Created (by another user)
────────────────────────────────────────────────
Requester submits Request.js form (bloodGroup, hospital, urgency)
→ POST /api/requests/create (JWT required)
→ Request saved in MongoDB with GeoJSON coordinates
→ notifyController fires → queries User collection:
   • blood group match (or compatible)
   • available: true
   • within distance radius
   • reliabilityScore sorted desc
→ sendMail() to each matched donor → personalised HTML email with YES/NO links

STEP 6: Donor Responds to Email
─────────────────────────────────
Donor sees email → clicks "YES — I WILL DONATE"
→ GET /api/notify/offer/respond?token=<secure_token>&resp=yes
→ Server: finds Offer by token, updates response=yes, status=accepted
→ Donor assigned as primary in Request document
→ Email to requester: "Donor found! Here are their details"
→ Email to donor: "You're the primary donor! Navigate to hospital"

STEP 7: Donation in Progress
──────────────────────────────
Scheduler (every 5 min): checks if primary donor arrived within 2h
→ If not arrived: promotes backup donor, notifies failed primary
→ If arrived: POST /api/requests/verify-arrival/:id

STEP 8: Donation Completed
───────────────────────────
POST /api/requests/complete/:id
→ Request status → "fulfilled"
→ User.donationsCount++, heroCoins += 50, leaderboardPoints++
→ reliabilityScore stays high
→ tplRewardEarned email: "You earned 50 Hero Coins!"
→ tplRequesterReward email: "Your request was fulfilled!"
→ Gamification page updated with new badges/coins

STEP 9: Follow-up
──────────────────
server.mjs background processor: after 24h, checks unconfirmed Offers
→ Sends reminder email: "Are you still able to donate?"
→ Requester receives follow-up: "Did the donation happen?"
→ Honest feedback updates donor reliability score
```

---

## Quick Viva Q&A Reference

**Q: How is OTP secured?**
A: Generated using `crypto.randomInt()` (cryptographically secure), hashed with bcrypt(10) and stored in DB. Never stored in plaintext. Expires in 10 min, max 5 attempts, cleared after use.

**Q: How does authentication work?**
A: JWT-based. After login/OTP-verify, server issues a JWT (signed with `JWT_SECRET`, expires 7d). Frontend stores in localStorage, sends as `Authorization: Bearer <token>`. `authMiddleware.mjs` verifies on every protected route.

**Q: How are donors matched?**
A: MongoDB `$geoNear` aggregation with `available: true` filter, sorted by distance. Additional blood-group compatibility mapping in `notifyController`.

**Q: How does the email flow work?**
A: `emailNotifier.mjs` uses `@sendgrid/mail` SDK. `sendMail()` is called asynchronously (non-blocking) — frontend gets response immediately while email sends in background.

**Q: What happens if a donor doesn't show up?**
A: `scheduler.mjs` runs every 5 minutes. If primary donor's `acceptedAt` was >2 hours ago and `arrived=false`, backup donor is promoted to primary, failed primary gets notification email, request status updated.

**Q: Where is data stored?**
A: MongoDB Atlas (cloud). All collections in one database. Mongoose ODM (Object Document Mapper) provides schema validation and model methods.

**Q: What is the Watcher system?**
A: Donors in post-donation cooldown (90-day wait period) can "watch" a request. If request stays `open` for 6+ hours, scheduler emails all watchers encouraging them to reconsider donating.
